The Problem

The goal of this assignment is to create a regression model that would accurately predict housing prices in Kings County, Washington.

Research question: How do features indicating characteristics of homes sold (bedrooms, year of contruction, grade…) effect house price?

The data

For this analysis we will use king.csv file which contains data on sales in in Kings County, Washington from 5/2/2014 to 5/27/2015.

The response variable is:

  • price: Selling price of the house.

And the explanatory variables are:

  • id: Unique ID for a house.

  • bedrooms: Number of bedrooms.

  • bathrooms: Number of bathrooms.

  • sqft_living: square footage of the home.

  • sqft_lot: square footage of the lot.

  • floors: Total floors (levels) in house.

  • waterfront: Whether house has a view to a waterfront.

  • view: Number of times house has been viewed.

  • condition: How good the condition is (overall).

  • grade: overall grade given to the housing unit, based on King County grading system.

  • sqft_above: square footage of house (apart from basement).

  • sqft_basement: square footage of the basement.

  • yr_built: Year when house was built.

  • yr_renovated: Year when house was renovated.

  • zipcode: zip code in which house is located.

  • lat: Latitude coordinate.

  • long: Longitude coordinate.

  • sqft_living15: The square footage of interior housing living space for the nearest 15 neighbors.

  • sqft_lot15: The square footage of the land lots of the nearest 15 neighbors.

  • sqft_above: square footage of house (apart from basement).

  • sqft_basement: square footage of the basement.

Cleaning the data

To clean our data, we will remove the outliers of the variable rooms and for the variable bathrooms, we will replace those values less than 1 by 1. We will also remove the variables id, X and zip code as they do not provide us with any information regarding the problem we want to solve. In the case of id and X, they do not contribute because they are indexes and in the case of the postal code, it does not contribute anything because we already have the position coordinates which are more exact and contribute more than the postal code.

Distribution of the variables and relationship to the dependent variable

Now that we have our data cleaned, let’s analyse them one by one in order to better understand their distributions and their significance with respect to the dependent variable.For the distributions we will use a histogram, which will allow us to analyse them from an optical point of view, and for their relationship with the price variable we will use a scatterplot.

len <- length(colnames(data))
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

for(i in 1:len){
  column = colnames(data)[i]
  main = paste("Histogram of",column,sep=" ")
  hist(data[,i],main=main,xlab = column,col="#5C5E32")
  main = paste("Scatterplot of",column,sep=" ")
  plot(data$price ~ data[,i],main=main, data=data,
   xlab=column, ylab="Price", col = "#33D4FF")
}

As we can see, not all the independent variables present a perfectly linear relationship with respect to the dependent variable, but we can see a clear trend in most of them, for example in the number of bathrooms or the number of square metres of living space, where the trend is increasing with respect to the price.

If the residuals are distributed according to a normal distribution we should expect the median to be 0 or very close to 0, and the 1st and 3rd quartiles to be symmetric. The same for the minimum or maximum values. In this case there are notable deviations of mean and median and there is no symmetry between quartiles so it is very likely that we are not complying with some of the assumptions of the linear models.Another interesting fact that we can extract from the summary is that the intercept appears as negative, this does not seem to indicate that something is wrong with our model since our price variable does not make sense in a negative value. However, we can observe an adjusted R-squared of 0.696, which tells us that a percentage of 69.6% of the variation of the dependent variable is collectively explained by all the independent variables, so we can consider that the model does not perform badly at all.

This may be due to the fact that although we are using the variables that are most correlated with respect to the dependent variable assuming that each feature’s individual contribution to the outcome, we are ignoring the possibility that features could have a combined impact on the dependent variable.

Third attempt

We will introduce into the model some interaction effects in order to check whether the model does indeed improve by introducing these combinations. For this purpose, I will assume that there is an interaction between the number of floors and the square metres, since I assume that a house with exactly the same number of square metres could have a higher price if it has more floors. I will also assume the same between the square metres of land and the grade it has, and likewise with the number of bedrooms and the number of bathrooms, as I assume that a house with 5 bedrooms and only one bathroom cannot have the same value as one with the same number of bedrooms but with 5 bathrooms.

data2 <- data
data2$conbuil <- (data$sqft_living*data$floors)
data2$sqftGr <- (data$sqft_lot*data$grade)
data2$bedbath <- (data$bedrooms*data$bathrooms)
model3 <- lm(price~., data = data2)
summary(model3)

Fifth attempt

This time we will apply first a logarithmic transformation, this is a convenient means of transforming a highly skewed variable into a more normalized distribution. Using the logarithm of price variable we expect to improve the fit of the model by transforming the distribution to a more normally-shaped bell curve.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
hist(data$price, main = "Original price histogram", xlab = "Price", col ="#5C5E32")
data4$price <- log(data4$price)
hist(data4$price, main = "Transformed price histogram", xlab = "Price", col = "purple")

Finally, we will generate our model with this new distribution of the price variable, and then we will check the results.

data5 <- data4
model5 <- lm(data5$price~., data = data5)
summary(model5)

In the end we have managed to solve the problems regarding the distribution of the residuals, as they are now distributed according to a normal distribution since the median is close to 0, and the 1st and 3rd quartiles are symmetric, in addition, the model has improved its results significantly a percentage of 77.59% of the variation of the dependent variable is collectively explained now by all the independent variables. It seems that the problem lay in the distribution of the values of the price variable.

Conclusion

For our final model we have applied a transformation to the dependent variable in order to obtain a new distribution that is more favourable for our model. Thanks to this transformation we have been able to get our residuals to follow a distribution closer to the normal distribution and we have also improved the results with respect to the R-squared that we had obtained previously. It is also important to mention that the data regarding the square metres in our last model were squared, which, as we have already mentioned, allowed us to improve the model since these variables do not seem to have a linear relationship with respect to price.

As for the three coefficients to be mentioned, firstly, the number of habitable square metres of the house (sqft_living), it is quite intuitive to understand that the more habitable metres, the higher the price of the house, and this is confirmed by the coefficient assigned by the model to this variable, we can see this increase reflected in the coefficient, since being \(2.082\cdot10^{-4}\) we can be know that if the rest of the variables remained stable, for each unit that the square metres variable increased, the price would increase by \(e^{2.082\cdot10^{-4}}\). On the other hand, the other two coefficients that I would like to mention are latitude (lat) and longitude (long), since on the one hand latitude has a positive coefficient and the other negative, from here we can extract very valuable information since with this what we know is that a house with the same characteristics will be more expensive the more its latitude increases, since with an increase of one unit in the lat, price would increase according to our model by \(e^{1.363}\), on the other hand the same house also with the rest of the variables fixed would decrease its price by \(e^{6.383\cdot10^{-2}}\) for each unit of longitude that increases, knowing this we can make estimations to find a region that offers better prices for the same type of house.

Finally, as for the recommendations on how to improve the selling price of the house, in addition to those mentioned above which are related to its geographical position, I would also add, taking into account the results obtained by the model, that the price can be increased by the number of flats, which if there is no special interest in this, could save money by simply buying a house with only one flat but the same square metres, and I would also consider reviewing the cost of renovating a house on your own, as perhaps you can save a lot if you buy a house without renovating it.
